# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: incident-response
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Several business continuity standards have been published by various standards bodies to assist in checklisting ongoing planning tasks.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Business continuity requires a top-down approach to identify an organisation's minimum requirements to ensure its viability as an entity.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] An organization's resistance to failure is "the ability ... to withstand changes in its environment and still function".
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Often called resilience, resistance to failure is a capability that enables organizations to either endure environmental changes without having to permanently adapt, or the organization is forced to adapt a new way of working that better suits the new environmental conditions.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Any event that could negatively impact operations should be included in the plan, such as supply chain interruption, loss of or damage to critical infrastructure (major machinery or computing/network resource).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] As such, BCP is a subset of risk management.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] In the U.S., government entities refer to the process as *continuity of operations planning* (COOP).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] A **business continuity plan** outlines a range of disaster scenarios and the steps the business will take in any particular scenario to return to regular trade.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] BCP's are written ahead of time and can also include precautions to be put in place.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Usually created with the input of key staff as well as stakeholders, a BCP is a set of contingencies to minimize potential harm to businesses during adverse scenarios.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] A 2005 analysis of how disruptions can adversely affect the operations of corporations and how investments in resilience can give a competitive advantage over entities not prepared for various contingencies extended then-common business continuity planning practices.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Business organizations such as the Council on Competitiveness embraced this resilience goal.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] This approach is sometimes summarized as: preparedness, protection, response and recovery.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Resilience Theory can be related to the field of Public Relations.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Resilience is a communicative process that is constructed by citizens, families, media system, organizations and governments through everyday talk and mediated conversation.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The theory is based on the work of Patrice M.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Buzzanell, a professor at the Brian Lamb School of Communication at Purdue University.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] In her 2010 article, "Resilience: Talking, Resisting, and Imagining New Normalcies Into Being" Buzzanell discussed the ability for organizations to thrive after having a crisis through building resistance.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] While resilience theory and crisis communication theory share similarities, they are not the same.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The crisis communication theory is based on the reputation of the company, but the resilience theory is based on the process of recovery of the company.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] There are five main components of resilience: crafting normalcy, affirming identity anchors, maintaining and using communication networks, putting alternative logics to work, and downplaying negative feelings while foregrounding negative emotions.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Each of these processes can be applicable to businesses in crisis times, making resilience an important factor for companies to focus on while training.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] There are three main groups that are affected by a crisis.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] They are micro (individual), meso (group or organization) and macro (national or interorganizational).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] There are also two main types of resilience, which are proactive and post resilience.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Proactive resilience is preparing for a crisis and creating a solid foundation for the company.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Post resilience includes continuing to maintain communication and check in with employees.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Proactive resilience is dealing with issues at hand before they cause a possible shift in the work environment and post resilience maintaining communication and accepting changes after an incident has happened.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Resilience can be applied to any organization.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] In New Zealand, the Canterbury University Resilient Organisations programme developed an assessment tool for benchmarking the Resilience of Organisations.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] It covers 11 categories, each having 5 to 7 questions.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] A *Resilience Ratio* summarizes this evaluation.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Plans and procedures are used in business continuity planning to ensure that the critical organizational operations required to keep an organization running continue to operate during events when key dependencies of operations are disrupted.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Continuity does not need to apply to every activity which the organization undertakes.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] For example, under ISO 22301:2019, organizations are required to define their business continuity objectives, the minimum levels of product and service operations which will be considered acceptable and the maximum tolerable period of disruption (MTPD) which can be allowed.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] A major cost in planning for this is the preparation of audit compliance management documents; automation tools are available to reduce the time and cost associated with manually producing this information.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] A Business Impact Analysis (BIA) is a process used to identify and evaluate the effects of disruptions on an organization's operations, and to determine recovery priorities and strategies appropriate to the organizational needs.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Assess the impact of disruptions on these activities (financial, operational, reputational, legal).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Determine recovery time objectives (RTO) and recovery point objectives (RPO).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Support the development of business continuity strategies and plans.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Inform risk assessment and mitigation efforts within the BCMS framework.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] According to ISO 22301 the terms *maximum acceptable outage* and *maximum tolerable period of disruption* mean the same thing and are defined using exactly the same words.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Some standards use the term *maximum downtime limit*.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] When more than one system crashes, recovery plans must balance the need for data consistency with other objectives, such as RTO and RPO.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] **Recovery Consistency Objective** (RCO) is the name of this goal.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] It applies data consistency objectives, to define a measurement for the consistency of distributed business data within interlinked systems after a disaster incident.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Similar terms used in this context are "Recovery Consistency Characteristics" (RCC) and "Recovery Object Granularity" (ROG).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] While RTO and RPO are absolute per-system values, RCO is expressed as a percentage that measures the deviation between actual and targeted state of business data across systems for process groups or individual business processes.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] 100% RCO means that post recovery, no business data deviation occurs.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The purpose of the Risk Assessment phase is to identify risks that could lead to disruptions and to assess their likelihood and potential impact.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The main action of the Risk Assessment include: 1.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Identify internal and external threats (see Common Threats section).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Analyze vulnerabilities and potential consequences (e.g., not having a generator during a power outage).
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Assessing each risk by determining the likelihood of occurrence and the severity of its impact.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Prioritizing risks for treatment and mitigation.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The above areas can cascade: Responders can stumble.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] During the 2002–2003 SARS outbreak, some organizations compartmentalized and rotated teams to match the incubation period of the disease.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] They also banned in-person contact during both business and non-business hours.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] This increased resiliency against the threat.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] These should reflect the widest possible damage.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] This phase overlaps with disaster recovery planning.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] There are many standards that are available to support business continuity planning and management.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The British Standards Institution (BSI Group) released a series of standards which have since been withdrawn and replaced by the ISO standards above.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Within the UK, BS 25999-2:2007 and BS 25999-1:2006 were being used for business continuity management across all organizations, industries and sectors.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] These documents give a practical plan to deal with most eventualities—from extreme weather conditions to terrorism, IT system failure, and staff sickness.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] In 2004, following crises in the preceding years, the UK government passed the Civil Contingencies Act of 2004: Businesses must have continuity planning measures to survive and continue to thrive whilst working towards keeping the incident as minimal as possible.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The Act was separated into two parts: Part 1: civil protection, covering roles & responsibilities for local responders Part 2: emergency powers.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] In the United Kingdom, resilience is implemented locally by the Local Resilience Forum.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The implementation phase involves policy changes, material acquisitions, staffing and testing.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] The 2008 book *Exercising for Excellence*, published by The British Standards Institution identified three types of exercises that can be employed when testing business continuity plans.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] While start and stop times are pre-agreed, the actual duration might be unknown if events are allowed to run their course.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Biannual or annual maintenance cycle maintenance of a BCP manual is broken down into three periodic activities.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Issues found during the testing phase often must be reintroduced to the analysis phase.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Specialized technical resources must be maintained.
[src:incident-response/business-continuity-planning] Software and work process changes must be documented and validated, including verification that documented work process recovery tasks and supporting disaster recovery infrastructure allow staff to recover within the predetermined recovery time objective.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] A **computer emergency response team** (**CERT**) is an incident response team dedicated to computer security incidents.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] Other names used to describe CERT include **cyber emergency response team**, **computer emergency readiness team**, **computer security incident response team** (**CSIRT**), or **cyber security incident response team**.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] The name "Computer Emergency Response Team" was first used in 1988 by the CERT Coordination Center (CERT-CC) at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU).
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] The term CERT is registered as a trade and service mark by CMU in multiple countries worldwide.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] CMU encourages the use of Computer Security Incident Response Team (CSIRT) as a generic term for the handling of computer security incidents.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] CMU licenses the CERT mark to various organizations that are performing the activities of a CSIRT.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] The histories of CERT and CSIRT, are linked to the existence of malware, especially computer worms and viruses.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] Whenever a new technology arrives, its misuse is not long in following.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] The first worm in the IBM VNET was covered up.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] Shortly after, a worm hit the Internet on 3 November 1988, when the so-called Morris Worm paralysed a good percentage of it.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] This led to the formation of the first computer emergency response team at Carnegie Mellon University under a U.S.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] With the massive growth in the use of information and communications technologies over the subsequent years, the generic term 'CSIRT' refers to an essential part of most large organisations' structures.
[src:incident-response/computer-emergency-response-team] In many organisations the CSIRT evolves into an information security operations center.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In the fields of computer security and information technology, **computer security incident management** involves the monitoring and detection of security events on a computer or computer network, and the execution of proper responses to those events.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Computer security incident management is a specialized form of incident management, the primary purpose of which is the development of a well understood and predictable response to damaging events and computer intrusions.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Incident management requires a process and a response team which follows this process.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In the United States, This definition of computer security incident management follows the standards and definitions described in the National Incident Management System (NIMS).
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] The incident coordinator manages the response to an emergency security incident.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In a Natural Disaster or other event requiring response from Emergency services, the incident coordinator would act as a liaison to the emergency services incident manager.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] An incident response plan (IRP) is a group of policies that dictate an organizations reaction to a cyber attack.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Once a security breach has been identified, for example by network intrusion detection system (NIDS) or host-based intrusion detection system (HIDS) (if configured to do so), the plan is initiated.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] It is important to note that there can be legal implications to a data breach.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Knowing local and federal laws is critical.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Every plan is unique to the needs of the organization, and it can involve skill sets that are not part of an IT team.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] For example, a lawyer may be included in the response plan to help navigate legal implications to a data breach.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Good preparation includes the development of an incident response team (IRT).
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Skills need to be used by the IRT would be, penetration testing, computer forensics, network security, etc.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] The IRT should also keep track of trends in cybersecurity and modern attack strategies.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] A training program for end users is important as well as most modern attack strategies target users on the network.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This part of the incident response plan identifies if there was a security event.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] When an end user reports information or an admin notices irregularities, an investigation is launched.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] An incident log is a crucial part of this step.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] All of the members of the team should be updating this log to ensure that information flows as fast as possible.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] If it has been identified that a security breach has occurred the next step should be activated.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In this phase, the IRT works to isolate the areas that the breach took place to limit the scope of the security event.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] During this phase it is important to preserve information forensically so it can be analyzed later in the process.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Containment could be as simple as physically containing a server room or as complex as segmenting a network to not allow the spread of a virus.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This is where the threat that was identified is removed from the affected systems.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This could include deleting malicious files, terminating compromised accounts, or deleting other components.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Some events do not require this step, however it is important to fully understand the event before moving to this step.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This will help to ensure that the threat is completely removed.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This stage is where the systems are restored back to original operation.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In complex incidents such as ransomware attacks, recovery efforts may involve not only restoring data but also reconstructing compromised systems and performing forensic analysis to ensure the integrity of recovered information.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This stage could include the recovery of data, changing user access information, or updating firewall rules or policies to prevent a breach in the future.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Without executing this step, the system could still be vulnerable to future security threats.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] In this step information that has been gathered during this process is used to make future decisions on security.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This step is crucial to the ensure that future events are prevented.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Using this information to further train admins is critical to the process.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] This step can also be used to process information that is distributed from other entities who have experienced a security event.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] Incident response requirements vary by industry.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] A December 2024 Notice of Proposed Rulemaking would strengthen these requirements by mandating written incident response plans, requiring restoration of critical systems within 72 hours of an incident, and requiring regular testing and revision of contingency plans.
[src:incident-response/computer-security-incident-management] The 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack, which disrupted claims processing for healthcare providers across the United States for several weeks, highlighted the importance of robust incident response planning in the healthcare sector.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In computer science, a **cyberattack** (or **cyber attack**) is an attack targeted at computer systems.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] It occurs when there is an unauthorized action against computer infrastructure that compromises the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of its content.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The rising dependence on increasingly complex and interconnected computer systems in most domains of life is the main factor that causes vulnerability to cyberattacks, since virtually all computer systems have bugs that can be exploited by attackers.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Although it is impossible or impractical to create a perfectly secure system, there are many defense mechanisms that can make a system more difficult to attack, making information security a field of rapidly increasing importance in the world today.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Perpetrators of a cyberattack can be criminals, hacktivists, or states.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] They attempt to find weaknesses in a system, exploit them and create malware to carry out their goals, and deliver it to the targeted system.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Once installed, the malware can have a variety of effects depending on its purpose.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Detection of cyberattacks is often absent or delayed, especially when the malware attempts to spy on the system while remaining undiscovered.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] If it is discovered, the targeted organization may attempt to collect evidence about the attack, remove malware from its systems, and close the vulnerability that enabled the attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Cyberattacks can cause a variety of harms to targeted individuals, organizations, and governments, including significant financial losses and identity theft.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] They are usually illegal both as a method of crime and warfare, although correctly attributing the attack is difficult and perpetrators are rarely prosecuted.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] A cyberattack is any attempt by an individual or organization to use computers or digital systems to steal, alter, expose, disable, or destroy information, or to breach computer systems, networks, or infrastructures.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Definitions differ as to the type of compromise required – for example, requiring the system to produce unexpected responses or cause injury or property damage.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some definitions exclude attacks carried out by non-state actors and others require the target to be a state.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Keeping a system secure relies on maintaining the CIA triad: confidentiality (no unauthorized access), integrity (no unauthorized modification), and availability.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Although availability is less important for some web-based services, it can be the most crucial aspect for industrial systems.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In the first six months of 2017, two billion data records were stolen or impacted by cyber attacks, and ransomware payments reached US$2 billion, double that in 2016.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In 2020, with the increase of remote work as an effect of the COVID-19 global pandemic, cybersecurity statistics reveal a huge increase in hacked and breached data.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The worldwide information security market is forecast to reach $170.4 billion in 2022.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Over time, computer systems make up an increasing portion of daily life and interactions.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] While the increasing complexity and connectedness of the systems increases the efficiency, power, and convenience of computer technology, it also renders the systems more vulnerable to attack and worsens the consequences of an attack, should one occur.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Despite developers' goal of delivering a product that works entirely as intended, virtually all software and hardware contains bugs.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but those that remain unknown (zero days) as well as those that have not been patched are still liable for exploitation.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The software vendor is not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The most valuable allow the attacker to inject and run their own code (called malware), without the user being aware of it.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Without a vulnerability enabling access, the attacker cannot gain access to the system.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The Vulnerability Model (VM) identifies attack patterns, threats, and valuable assets, which can be physical or intangible.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] It addresses security concerns like confidentiality, integrity, availability, and accountability within business, application, or infrastructure contexts.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] A system's architecture and design decisions play a major role in determining how safe it can be.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The traditional approach to improving security is the detection of systems vulnerable to attack and hardening these systems to make attacks more difficult, but it is only partially effective.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Formal risk assessment for compromise of highly complex and interconnected systems is impractical and the related question of how much to spend on security is difficult to answer.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Because of the ever changing and uncertain nature of cyber-threats, risk assessment may produce scenarios that are costly or unaffordable to mitigate.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] As of 2019, there are no commercially available, widely used active defense systems for protecting systems by intentionally increasing the complexity or variability of systems to make it harder to attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The cyber resilience approach, on the other hand, assumes that breaches will occur and focuses on protecting essential functionality even if parts are compromised, using approaches such as micro-segmentation, zero trust, and business continuity planning.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The majority of attacks can be prevented by ensuring all software is fully patched.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Nevertheless, fully patched systems are still vulnerable to exploits using zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The highest risk of attack occurs just after a vulnerability has been publicly disclosed or a patch is released, because attackers can create exploits faster than a patch can be developed and rolled out.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Software solutions aim to prevent unauthorized access and detect the intrusion of malicious software.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Training users can avoid cyberattacks (for example, not to click on a suspicious link or email attachment), especially those that depend on user error.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] However, too many rules can cause employees to disregard them, negating any security improvement.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some insider attacks can also be prevented using rules and procedures.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Disconnecting systems from the internet is one truly effective measure against attacks, but it is rarely feasible.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In some jurisdictions, there are legal requirements for protecting against attacks.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The cyber kill chain is the process by which perpetrators carry out cyberattacks.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Weaponization: after finding a vulnerability, attackers build an exploit to gain access, and malware to carry out the attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Delivery: once complete, the malware is delivered to the target.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Most data breaches and malware insertions are enabled by phishing, where the attacker sends a malicious communication, often an email, in an attempt to get the recipient to click on a link or attachment to deliver malware.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Drive-by-download does not require any clicks, only a visit to a malicious website.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Sometimes insiders are behind the attack and can use their credentials to bypass security.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some attacks are delivered indirectly via associated companies that have a business relationship with the target.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Others may be delivered by directly accessing hardware, particularly in the cases of bribery or blackmail.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Exploitation: the attacker's software is executed on the targeted system, and often creates a backdoor to enable remote control by the attacker.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Many attackers will not launch an attack right away.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The attacker often seeks to persist after system interruption (such as crash or restart), evade detection, and escalate privileges, and secure multiple channels of communication with its controllers.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Other common actions include responding to remote controls and collecting and copying data to a device controlled by the attacker (data exfiltration).
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] After the malware is installed, its activity varies greatly depending on the attacker's goals.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Many attackers try to eavesdrop on a system without affecting it.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Although this type of malware can have unexpected side effects, it is often very difficult to detect.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Botnets are networks of compromised devices that can be used to send spam or carry out denial-of-service attacks—flooding a system with too many requests for the system to handle at once, causing it to become unusable.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Attackers may also use computers to mine cryptocurrencies, such as Bitcoin, for their own profit.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Ransomware is software used to encrypt or destroy data; attackers demand payment for the restoration of the targeted system.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The advent of cryptocurrency enabling anonymous transactions has led to a dramatic increase in ransomware demands.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The stereotype of a hacker is an individual working for one's self.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] However, many cyber threats are teams of well-resourced experts.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] "Growing revenues for cyber criminals are leading to more and more attacks, increasing professionalism and highly specialized attackers.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In addition, unlike other forms of crime, cybercrime can be carried out remotely, and cyber attacks often scale well." Many cyberattacks are caused or enabled by insiders, often employees who bypass security procedures to get their job done more efficiently.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Attackers vary widely in their skill and sophistication and well as their determination to attack a particular target, as opposed to opportunistically picking one easy to attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The skill level of the attacker determined which types of attacks they are prepared to mount.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The most sophisticated attackers can persist undetected on a hardened system for an extended period of time.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Depending whether the expected threat is passive espionage, data manipulation, or active hijacking, different mitigation methods may be needed.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Software vendors and governments are mainly interested in undisclosed vulnerabilities (zero-days), while organized crime groups are more interested in ready-to-use exploit kits based on known vulnerabilities, which are much cheaper.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The lack of transparency in the market causes problems, such as buyers being unable to guarantee that the zero-day vulnerability was not sold to another party.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Both buyers and sellers advertise on the dark web and use cryptocurrency for untraceable transactions.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Because of the difficulty in writing and maintaining software that can attack a wide variety of systems, criminals found they could make more money by renting out their exploits rather than using them directly.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Cybercrime as a service, where hackers sell prepacked software that can be used to cause a cyberattack, is increasingly popular as a lower risk and higher profit activity than traditional hacking.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] A major form of this is to create a botnet of compromised devices and rent or sell it to another cybercriminal.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Different botnets are equipped for different tasks such as DDOS attacks or password cracking.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] It is also possible to buy the software used to create a botnet and bots that load the purchaser's malware onto a botnet's devices.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] DDOS as a service using botnets retained under the control of the seller is also common, and may be the first cybercrime as a service product, and can also be committed by SMS flooding on the cellular network.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Malware and ransomware as a service have made it possible for individuals without technical ability to carry out cyberattacks.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Targets of cyberattacks range from individuals to corporations and government entities.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Many cyberattacks are foiled or unsuccessful, but those that succeed can have devastating consequences.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Understanding the negative effects of cyberattacks helps organizations ensure that their prevention strategies are cost-effective.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Thousands of data records are stolen from individuals every day.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] According to a 2020 estimate, 55 percent of data breaches were caused by organized crime, 10 percent by system administrators, 10 percent by end users such as customers or employees, and 10 percent by states or state-affiliated actors.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Opportunistic criminals may cause data breaches—often using malware or social engineering attacks, but they will typically move on if the security is above average.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] More organized criminals have more resources and are more focused in their targeting of particular data.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Both of them sell the information they obtain for financial gain.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Another source of data breaches are politically motivated hackers, for example Anonymous, that target particular objectives.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] State-sponsored hackers target either citizens of their country or foreign entities, for such purposes as political repression and espionage.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] After a data breach, criminals make money by selling data, such as usernames, passwords, social media or customer loyalty account information, debit and credit card numbers, and personal health information (see medical data breach).
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] This information may be used for a variety of purposes, such as spamming, obtaining products with a victim's loyalty or payment information, prescription drug fraud, insurance fraud, and especially identity theft.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Consumer losses from a breach are usually a negative externality for the business.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Critical infrastructure is that considered most essential—such as healthcare, water supply, transport, and financial services—which has been increasingly governed by cyber-physical systems that depend on network access for their functionality.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] For years, writers have warned of cataclysmic consequences of cyberattacks that have failed to materialize as of 2023.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] These extreme scenarios could still occur, but many experts consider that it is unlikely that challenges in inflicting physical damage or spreading terror can be overcome.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Smaller-scale cyberattacks, sometimes resulting in interruption of essential services, regularly occur.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] There is little empirical evidence of economic harm (such as reputational damage) from breaches except the direct cost for such matters as legal, technical, and public relations recovery efforts.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Studies that have attempted to correlate cyberattacks to short-term declines in stock prices have found contradictory results, with some finding modest losses, others finding no effect, and some researchers criticizing these studies on methodological grounds.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The effect on stock price may vary depending on the type of attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some experts have argued that the evidence suggests there is not enough direct costs or reputational damage from breaches to sufficiently incentivize their prevention.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Government websites and services are among those affected by cyberattacks.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some experts hypothesize that cyberattacks weaken societal trust or trust in the government, but as of 2023 this notion has only limited evidence.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Responding quickly to attacks is an effective way to limit the damage.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] The response is likely to require a wide variety of skills, from technical investigation to legal and public relations.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Because of the prevalence of cyberattacks, some companies plan their incident response before any attack is detected, and may designate a computer emergency response team to be prepared to handle incidents.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Of those that are, the average time to discovery is 197 days.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Some systems can detect and flag anomalies that may indicate an attack, using such technology as antivirus, firewall, or an intrusion detection system.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Once suspicious activity is suspected, investigators look for indicators of attack and indicators of compromise.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Discovery is quicker and more likely if the attack targets information availability (for example with a denial-of-service attack) rather than integrity (modifying data) or confidentiality (copying data without changing it).
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] State actors are more likely to keep the attack secret.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Sophisticated attacks using valuable exploits are more less likely to be detected or announced – as the perpetrator wants to protect the usefulness of the exploit.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Evidence collection is done immediately, prioritizing volatile evidence that is likely to be erased quickly.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Gathering data about the breach can facilitate later litigation or criminal prosecution, but only if the data is gathered according to legal standards and the chain of custody is maintained.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Containing the affected system is often a high priority after an attack, and may be enacted by shutoff, isolation, use of a sandbox system to find out more about the adversary patching the vulnerability, and rebuilding.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Once the exact way that the system was compromised is identified, there is typically only one or two technical vulnerabilities that need to be addressed in order to contain the breach and prevent it from reoccurring.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] A penetration test can then verify that the fix is working as expected.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] If malware is involved, the organization must investigate and close all infiltration and exfiltration vectors, as well as locate and remove all malware from its systems.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Containment can compromise investigation, and some tactics (such as shutting down servers) can violate the company's contractual obligations.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] After the breach is fully contained, the company can then work on restoring all systems to operational.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Maintaining a backup and having tested incident response procedures are used to improve recovery.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Attributing a cyberattack is difficult, and of limited interest to companies that are targeted by cyberattacks.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In contrast, secret services often have a compelling interest in finding out whether a state is behind the attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Unlike attacks carried out in person, determining the entity behind a cyberattack is difficult.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] A further challenge in attribution of cyberattacks is the possibility of a false flag attack, where the actual perpetrator makes it appear that someone else caused the attack.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Every stage of the attack may leave artifacts, such as entries in log files, that can be used to help determine the attacker's goals and identity.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In the aftermath of an attack, investigators often begin by saving as many artifacts as they can find, and then try to determine the attacker.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Law enforcement agencies may investigate cyber incidents although the hackers responsible are rarely caught.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Most states agree that cyberattacks are regulated under the laws governing the use of force in international law, and therefore cyberattacks as a form of warfare are likely to violate the prohibition of aggression.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Therefore, they could be prosecuted as a crime of aggression.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] There is also agreement that cyberattacks are governed by international humanitarian law, and if they target civilian infrastructure, they could be prosecuted as a war crime, crime against humanity, or act of genocide.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] International courts cannot enforce these laws without sound attribution of the attack, without which countermeasures by a state are not legal either.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In many countries, cyberattacks are prosecutable under various laws aimed at cybercrime.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Attribution of the attack beyond reasonable doubt to the accused is also a major challenge in criminal proceedings.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] In 2021, United Nations member states began negotiating a draft cybercrime treaty.
[src:incident-response/cyberattack] Many jurisdictions have data breach notification laws that require organizations to notify people whose personal data has been compromised in a cyberattack.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] An incident is an event that could lead to loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services, or functions.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] **Incident management** (**IcM**) refers to the activities an organization undertakes to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent future recurrence.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] These incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), an incident management team (IMT), or Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Without effective incident management, an incident can disrupt business operations, information security, IT systems, employees, customers, or other vital business functions.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] An incident is an event that may lead to the loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services or functions.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incident management (IcM) is a term describing the activities of an organization to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent a future re-occurrence.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] If not managed, an incident can escalate into an emergency, crisis or disaster.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incident management is therefore the process of limiting the potential disruption caused by such an event, followed by a return to business as usual.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Physical incident management is the real-time response that may last for hours, days, or longer.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The United Kingdom Cabinet Office has produced the National Recovery Guidance (NRG), which is aimed at local responders as part of the implementation of the Civil Contingencies Act 2004 (CCA).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] It describes the response as the following: "Response encompasses the actions taken to deal with the immediate effects of an emergency.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] In many scenarios, it is likely to be relatively short and to last for a matter of hours or days – rapid implementation of arrangements for collaboration, coordination and communication is, therefore, vital.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Response encompasses the effort to deal not only with the direct effects of the emergency itself (eg fighting fires, rescuing individuals) but also the indirect effects (eg disruption, media interest)".
[src:incident-response/incident-response] This again shows the importance of not just good planning but the effective allocation of resources to treat the risk.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incident management in critical infrastructure environments involves coordinated response activities designed to protect essential services whose disruption may impact public safety, economic stability, or national security.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Unlike incident management in purely informational or corporate IT contexts, critical infrastructure incidents often involve operational technology, physical processes, safety systems, and regulatory obligations.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Critical infrastructure incident management typically emphasizes early detection, structured escalation, cross-functional coordination, and continuity of operations.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incidents may originate from cyber events, physical failures, human error, natural hazards, or combined (hybrid) causes, requiring integrated response across engineering, operations, security, executive leadership, and external authorities.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Because infrastructure sectors are highly interdependent, incident management approaches in these environments often account for cascading effects across energy, communications, transportation, healthcare, and other essential services.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] As a result, planning and response activities commonly incorporate predefined roles, decision authorities, communication protocols, and recovery objectives aligned with safety and resilience requirements.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Today, an important role is played by a Computer Security Incident Response Team (CSIRT), due to the rise of internet crime, and is a common example of an incident faced by companies in developed nations all across the world.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] For example, if an organization discovers that an intruder has gained unauthorized access to a computer system, the CSIRT would analyze the situation, determine the breadth of the compromise, and take corrective action.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Currently, over half of the world's hacking attempts on Trans National Corporations (TNCs) have taken place in North America (57%).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] A Computer Security Incident Response team can provide a secure environment for an organization, and has become a large part of the design of many modern networking teams.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), or an incident management team (IMT).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] These are often designated beforehand or during the event and are placed in control of the organization while the incident is being addressed, to restore normal functions.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The incident commander manages the response to a security incident and leads the members of the incident response team(s) through the process, as defined by the Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Usually, as part of the wider management process in private organizations, incident management is followed by post-incident analysis where it is determined why the incident happened despite precautions and controls.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] This analysis is normally overseen by the leaders of the organization, with the view of preventing a repetition of the incident through precautionary measures and often changes in policy.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] This information is then used as feedback to further develop the security policy and/or its practical implementation.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] In the United States, the National Incident Management System, developed by the Department of Homeland Security, integrates effective practices in emergency management into a comprehensive national framework.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] This often results in a higher level of contingency planning, exercise and training, as well as an evaluation of the management of the incident.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incident management frameworks for critical infrastructure commonly follow a lifecycle-based approach that includes incident detection, classification, response coordination, containment, recovery, and post-incident review.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] These frameworks are designed to support timely decision-making while balancing safety, operational continuity, and regulatory compliance.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] In critical infrastructure contexts, such frameworks often integrate elements from emergency management systems, cybersecurity incident response practices, and operational risk management models.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The goal is to enable organizations to respond effectively under high-consequence conditions while maintaining control over complex technical and organizational dependencies.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Practitioner-oriented literature provides detailed guidance on applying lifecycle-based incident management frameworks within industrial and critical infrastructure environments, including considerations for operational technology, safety, and cross-sector coordination.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] During the root cause analysis, human factors should be assessed.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] James Reason conducted a study into the understanding of adverse effects of human factors.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The study found that major incident investigations, such as Piper Alpha and Kings Cross Underground Fire, made it clear that the causes of the accidents were distributed widely within and outside the organization.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] There are two types of events: active failure—an action that has immediate effects and has the likelihood to cause an accident—and latent or delayed action—events can take years to have an effect and are usually combined with triggering events that then cause the accident.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Latent failures are created as the result of decisions taken at the higher echelons of an organisation.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Their damaging consequences may lie dormant for a long time, only becoming evident when they combine with local triggering factors (e.g., the spring tide, the loading difficulties at Zeebrugge harbour, etc.) to breach the system's defences.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Decisions taken in the higher echelons of an organization can trigger the events towards an accident becoming more likely, the planning, scheduling, forecasting, designing, policymaking, etc., can have a slow burning effect.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The actual unsafe act that triggers an accident can be traced back through the organization and the subsequent failures can be exposed, showing the accumulation of latent failures within the system as a whole that led to the accident becoming more likely and ultimately happening.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Better improvement action can be applied, and reduce the likelihood of the event happening again.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] Incident management is an important part of IT service management (ITSM) process area.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The first goal of the incident management process is to restore a normal service operation as quickly as possible and to minimize the impact on business operations, thus ensuring that the best possible levels of service quality and availability are maintained.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] 'Normal service operation' is defined here as service operation within service-level agreement (SLA).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] It is one process area within the broader ITIL and ISO 20000 environment.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] an unplanned interruption to an IT service or reduction in the quality of an IT service or a failure of a Configuration Item that has not yet impacted an IT service (for example failure of one disk from a mirror set).
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The ITIL incident management process *ensures that normal service operation is restored as quickly as possible and the business impact is minimized.* **ITIL Service Operation*.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The HIPAA Breach Notification Rule further requires notification to affected individuals within 60 days when unsecured protected health information is compromised, with breaches affecting 500 or more individuals reported to HHS and the media.
[src:incident-response/incident-response] The proposed rule also mandates annual testing and revision of incident response and contingency plans.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In science and reliability engineering, **root-cause analysis** (**RCA**) is a method of problem solving used for identifying the root causes of faults or problems.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] It is widely used in IT operations, manufacturing, telecommunications, industrial process control, accident analysis (e.g., in aviation, rail transport, or nuclear plants), medical diagnosis, the healthcare industry (e.g., for epidemiology).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is a form of inductive inference (first create a theory, or *root*, based on empirical evidence, or *causes*) and deductive inference (test the theory, i.e., the underlying causal mechanisms, with empirical data).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Establish a causal graph between the root-cause and the problem.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA generally serves as input to a remediation process whereby corrective actions are taken to prevent the problem from recurring.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The name of this process varies between application domains.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] According to ISO/IEC 31010, RCA may include these techniques: five whys, failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA), fault tree analysis, Ishikawa diagrams, and Pareto analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] There are essentially two ways of repairing faults and solving problems in science and engineering.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Reactive management consists of reacting quickly after the problem occurs, by treating the symptoms.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This type of management is implemented by reactive systems, self-adaptive systems, self-organized systems, and complex adaptive systems.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The goal here is to react quickly and alleviate the effects of the problem as soon as possible.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Proactive management, conversely, consists of preventing problems from occurring.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Many techniques can be used for this purpose, ranging from good practices in design to analyzing in detail problems that have already occurred and taking actions to make sure they never recur.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Speed is not as important here as the accuracy and precision of the diagnosis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The focus is on addressing the real cause of the problem rather than its effects.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is often used in proactive management to identify the root cause of a problem, that is, the factor that was the leading cause.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] It is customary to refer to the "root cause" in singular form, but one or several factors may constitute the *root cause(s)* of the problem under study.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A factor is considered the "root cause" of a problem if removing it prevents the problem from recurring.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Conversely, a "causal factor" is a contributing action that affects an incident/event's outcome but is not the root cause.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Although removing a causal factor can benefit an outcome, it does not prevent its recurrence with certainty.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A great way to look at the proactive/reactive picture is to consider the Bowtie Risk Assessment model.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In the center of the model is the event or accident.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] To the left, are the anticipated hazards and the line of defenses put in place to prevent those hazards from causing events.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The line of defense is the regulatory requirements, applicable procedures, physical barriers, and cyber barriers that are in place to manage operations and prevent events.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A great way to use root-cause analysis is to proactively evaluate the effectiveness of those defenses by comparing actual performance against applicable requirements, identifying performance gaps, and then closing the gaps to strengthen those defenses.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] If an event occurs, then we are on the right side of the model, the reactive side where the emphasis is on identifying the root causes and mitigating the damage.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Imagine an investigation into a machine that stopped because it was overloaded and the fuse blew.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Investigation shows that the machine was overloaded because it had a bearing that was not being sufficiently lubricated.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The investigation proceeds further and finds that the automatic lubrication mechanism had a pump that was not pumping sufficiently, hence the lack of lubrication.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of the pump shows that it has a worn shaft.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of why the shaft was worn discovers that there is not an adequate mechanism to prevent metal scrap getting into the pump; this enabled scrap to get into the pump and damage it.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The apparent root cause of the problem is that metal scrap can contaminate the lubrication system.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Fixing this problem ought to prevent the whole sequence of events from recurring.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The *real* root cause could be a design issue if there is no filter to prevent the metal scrap getting into the system.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Or if it has a filter that was blocked due to a lack of routine inspection, then the *real* root cause is a maintenance issue.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Compare this with an investigation that does not find the root cause: replacing the fuse, the bearing, or the lubrication pump will probably allow the machine to go back into operation for a while.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] However, there is a risk that the problem will simply recur until the root cause is dealt with.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In general terms, for the investigating team, such as quality and engineering personnel, vernacularly speaking, it commonly takes around 5 times asking "why".
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The above example does not include cost/benefit analysis: does the cost of replacing one or more machines exceed the cost of downtime until the fuse is replaced?
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This situation is sometimes referred to as *the cure being worse than the disease*.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This can help explain the problem of the cure being worse than the disease.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Costs to consider go beyond finances when considering the personnel who operate the machinery.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Ultimately, the goal is to prevent downtime; but more so prevent catastrophic injuries.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Despite the different approaches among the various schools of root-cause analysis and the specifics of each application domain, RCA generally follows the same steps.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Effective problem statements and event descriptions (as failures, for example) are helpful and usually required to ensure the execution of appropriate root-cause analyses.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Problem statements are the North Star of the RCA as it keeps the team focused on what they are investigating and prevents them from going astray.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Most RCAs begin with a fact finding session to gather available information such as witness statements, the chronology of events and applicable requirements for the evolutions that were taking place at the time of the event.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The information can be used to establish a sequence of events or timeline for the event, and to identify the line of the defenses that should have prevented the event (i.e. the administrative requirements, and physical and cyber barriers).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Available databases should also be queried and analyzed (such as corrective action program and safety program databases), and data analysis tools such as Pareto charts, process maps, fault trees, and other tools that provide insights into performance gaps.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Any number of data analysis tools can be brought to bear, including data analysis tools from Lean Six Sigma, statistical analysis tools, and others such as hierarchical clustering and data-mining solutions (such as graph-theory-based data mining).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Another consists in comparing the situation under investigation with past situations stored in case libraries, using case-based reasoning tools and can include change analysis, comparative timeline analysis and task analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] After identifying the defenses in place that should have prevented the event or accident, an analysis of defenses (traditionally called Barrier Analysis) can be conducted in every case, including non-RCA investigations.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] These initial gaps in performance are merely symptoms of deeper-seated causes.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] These symptomatic performance gaps are used to develop lines of inquiry questions as outlined below, to pursue the symptoms back to their points of origin (i.e. the root causes) using cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] After gathering available information, organizing it into charts with timelines and other data, after analyzing available data, and after conducting an analysis of defenses, those insights are used to generate questions.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] These questions become lines of inquiry for cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] There should not be any curiosity questions, questions that reflect "confirmation bias" (i.e. asking a leading question so they answer what the RCA team thinks are the causes), or questions that are accusatory in nature that will cause those helping the investigation to close down and withdraw.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Once a robust set of lines of inquiry questions has been developed from the factual evidence collected, the applicable requirements, and an analysis of the available data, those questions can be taken to the organization's subject matter experts.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This begins the process of cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Once a question is posed to the affected organization, their answer is used to pose a follow-up Socratic questions.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Socratic questions keep the investigation flowing down to the next deeper causal factors until the organization runs out of answers, or the last causal factor is beyond the organization's control.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] There are many skills involved in conducting an effective cause-and-effect analysis, including facilitation skills, communication skills, and Socratic questioning.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] When conducted properly, this will take the RCA down to the deepest-seated root causes.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A word of caution: Ishikawa or the Fishbone Diagram, and the 5-Whys methods, are not rigorous enough for conducting a root-cause analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The Fishbone is from the 1940s and the 5-Whys is from the 1930, and there are much more advanced methods available.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Look for methods that were developed in this century (the year 2000 and later), as they are more likely to account for the new dynamics of the modern sociotechnical work environments.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The best way to chart the results of an RCA investigation is to start populating the final chart from the start.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This process has become much easier with the advent of virtual whiteboards.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In a single virtual whiteboard, the timelines, lines of defenses, data analysis, lines of inquiry questions, cause-and-effect analysis, root causes, and corrective action plan can be displayed.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The Extent of Cause reviews are conducted to determine the extent of the damage or impact that the root causes and contributing factors had on humans, equipment, or facilities.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Extent of Cause reviews are an Achilles heel in the vast majority of organizations and a primary reason why RCAs and corrective action plans fail to prevent recurrence.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Also, care must be taken to avoid corrective action plans that simply add more administrative requirements and more training to the organization.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] To avoid this, use the Hierarchy of Hazard Controls and Lean Mistake Proofing as guidelines for developing effective corrective actions that have a much higher likelihood of preventing recurrence.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] After a pre-determined period after the implementation of the corrective action plan, an effectiveness review is scheduled to evaluate the effectiveness of those corrective actions.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] This requires specifying a set of metrics or indicators that will be monitored prior to and after the corrective actions are implemented, so their impact can be measured.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] If the desired results are not achieved, which in most cases is a significant reduction in the magnitude or frequency of the event or problem, then the RCA must be reopened as it was not effective.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] To be effective, root-cause analysis must be performed systematically.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The process enables the chance to not miss any other important details.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A team effort is typically required, and ideally all persons involved should arrive at the same conclusion.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In aircraft accident analyses, for example, the conclusions of the investigation and the root causes that are identified must be backed up by documented evidence.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The goal of RCA is to identify the root cause of the problem with the intent to stop the problem from recurring or worsening.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The next step is to trigger long-term corrective actions to address the root cause identified during RCA, and make sure that the problem does not resurface.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Correcting a problem is not formally part of RCA, however; these are different steps in a problem-solving process known as fault management in IT and telecommunications, repair in engineering, remediation in aviation, environmental remediation in ecology, therapy in medicine, etc.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is used in many application domains.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is specifically called out in the United States Code of Federal Regulations in many of the Titles.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 14 - AERONAUTICS AND SPACE >>> 14 CFR Chapter III, Subchapter C, Part 437, Subpart C, §437.73 Anomaly recording, reporting and implementation of corrective actions.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] A permittee must identify all root causes of each anomaly and implement all corrective actions for each anomaly.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 21 - FOOD AND DRUG >>> 21 CFR Subpart J: 21CFR820.100(a) – Corr./Preventive Action: (A) Each manufacturer shall establish and maintain procedures for implementing corrective and preventive action.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] The example above illustrates how RCA can be used in manufacturing.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also routinely used in industrial process control, e.g. to control the production of chemicals (quality control).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used for failure analysis in engineering and maintenance.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is frequently used in IT and telecommunications to detect the root causes of serious problems.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] For example, in the ITIL service management framework, the goal of incident management is to resume a faulty IT service as soon as possible (reactive management), whereas problem management deals with solving recurring problems for good by addressing their root causes (proactive management).
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Another example is the computer security incident management process, where root-cause analysis is often used to investigate security breaches.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in conjunction with business activity monitoring and complex event processing to analyze faults in business processes.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Its use in the IT industry cannot always be compared to its use in safety critical industries, since in normality the use of RCA in IT industry is *not* supported by pre-existing fault trees or other design specs.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Instead a mixture of debugging, event based detection and monitoring systems (where the services are individually modelled) is normally supporting the analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Training and supporting tools like simulation or different in-depth runbooks for all expected scenarios do not exist, instead they are created after the fact based on issues seen as 'worthy'.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] As a result the analysis is often limited to those things that have monitoring/observation interfaces and not the actual planned/seen function with focus on verification of inputs and outputs.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Hence, the saying "there is no root cause" has become common in the IT industry.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In the domains of health and safety, RCA is routinely used in medicine (diagnosis) and epidemiology (e.g., to identify the source of an infectious disease), where causal inference methods often require both clinical and statistical expertise to make sense of the complexities of the processes.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is used in environmental science (e.g., to analyze environmental disasters), accident analysis (aviation and rail industry), and occupational safety and health.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In the manufacture of medical devices, pharmaceuticals, food, and dietary supplements, root-cause analysis is a regulatory requirement.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in change management, risk management, and systems analysis.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Without delving in the idiosyncrasies of specific problems, several general conditions can make RCA more difficult than it may appear at first sight.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] First, important information is often missing because it is generally not possible, in practice, to monitor everything and store all monitoring data for a long time.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Second, gathering data and evidence, and classifying them along a timeline of events to the final problem, can be nontrivial.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] In telecommunications, for instance, distributed monitoring systems typically manage between a million and a billion events per day.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Finding a few relevant events in such a mass of irrelevant events is asking to find the proverbial needle in a haystack.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Third, there may be more than one root cause for a given problem, and this multiplicity can make the causal graph very difficult to establish.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Fourth, causal graphs often have many levels, and root-cause analysis terminates at a level that is "root" to the eyes of the investigator.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Switching vendors may have been due to management's desire to save money, and a failure to consult with engineering staff on the implication of the change on maintenance procedures.
[src:incident-response/root-cause-analysis] Thus, while the "root cause" shown above may have prevented the quoted recurrence, it would not have prevented other – perhaps more severe – failures affecting other machines.
